Sunday, January 1, 1956

Worked on the index to the rattler book all day. Finished page-numbering the galleys on which I had inserted key words before the page proofs became available.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:09 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Monday, January 2, 1956

Worked all day on the actual indexing--that is making out the small sheets to be rearranged alphabetically. Got part way into Chapter 4.

Went to the Lawson's to see slides tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:10 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Tuesday, January 3, 1956

At the office this morning and a Gas Co directors meeting at noon. Only catch up work today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:11 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, January 4, 1956

At the office this morning.

Finished indexing Chapter 4. Find it difficult to the entries down to a feasible figure. I am cutting out many that I had entered in the margins.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:12 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, January 5, 1956

At the office this morning.
Finished indexing Chapter 5.
Tonight went to a buffet supper at Roger Revell's, La Jolla, to meet Dr. Robert Cushman Murphy, the ornithologist.

Wrote Jo Ann Pope about mailing lists.

Friday, January 6, 1956

At the office in the morning.

Finished indexing chapter 6 and began on 7.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:23 PM

Saturday, January 7, 1956

Got halfway through indexing chapter 7.

Not a good day; many interruptions and outside interests.

Howard Chernoff came in to talk Children's Zoo.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:24 PM

Sunday, January 8, 1956

Finished indexing Chapter 7 and started Chapter 8.

Also did miscellaneous accounting.

  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:25 PM

Monday, January 9, 1956

Meeting of the proposed isotope group in Andy Borthwick's office at 10 AM. Zoo board met from 12 to 2:15. Natural History board 4 to 5. So nothing else done today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:27 PM

Tuesday, January 10, 1956

At the office in the morning.

Finished indexing chapter 8 in the afternoon.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:28 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, January 11, 1956

Received this morning at 7:30 the second page proofs of vol. II, to the end of the text, but not including the bibliography. Got only one copy which must be returned. This came first-class special ($7.10) so I suppose another copy to be retained will be along later. Also got an important letter from Jennings on some of the troubles with worn mats.

Went to Los Angeles on the 11:45 train and attended a meeting of the board of directors of Founders. Returned on the 5:30 train, arriving at 8:15.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:20 PM
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:32 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, January 12, 1956

Had a 30 minute talk with Jennings at Berkeley this morning. Many items discussed. Notes were made and filed.

Spent the rest of the morning in a meeting of the Gas Co. Executive Committee.

Dr. Comstock called at home at 1:30 and we discussed editorial forms and standards for the Natural History Museum Transactions.

Worked the rest of the afternoon and evening correcting and checking the second page proof of volume 2 and made considerable progress.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:21 PM
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Friday, January 13, 1956

Another talk with Jennings this morning. Among other things he told me to use my own judgment with regard to the index.

At the office this morning.

In the afternoon worked on the checking of the second page proof of volume 2, which was almost finished.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:38 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Saturday, January 14, 1956

Finished checking the second page proof of volume 2 and mailed it back to Berkeley. Also wrote letters to Jennings and Mrs. Carroll.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:21 PM

Sunday, January 15, 1956

Worked long and hard today on the index to chapter 9 and made good progress. It offers many tough problems to avoid being too voluminous.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:40 PM

Monday, January 16, 1956

At the office in the morning.

Meeting of the Library Commission from 2 to 5:10 this afternoon.

Little progress on the index.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:41 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

17th

Went to a Solar board of directors meeting from 9:30 AM to 2:20 P.M. Price appointed chairman of the board and Herb Kunzel president.

Went to the office in the afternoon.

Little progress on the index.

Next year's Grand Jury panel reduced from 60 to 30 and I was dropped out in the drawing, greatly to my relief.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:22 PM

Wednesday, January 18, 1956

At the office this morning.

Recd letters from Frugi and Jennings. Frugi wants to raise the price to $17.50.

Also received the third galley proof of the bibliography.

Made some headway on indexing chapter 9, but it is difficult and voluminous.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:47 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, January 19, 1956

At the office all morning.

KW directors meeting in the afternoon. Made some headway on the index of chapter 9 afterwards, but not much.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:48 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Friday, January 20, 1956

At the office all morning.

Continued today with the indexing of chapter 9, which has proved unusually difficult. It has necessitated the fixing of standards of arrangement. Finally completed it today.

Tonight began the preparation and arrangement of data on smog for use in a talk with Scholia Club tomorrow night.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:50 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Saturday, January 21, 1956

Worked all day on the preparation of a paper on smog for the Scholia Club. Just got it finished in time for presentation tonight. It went off fairly satisfactorily but was too non-controversial to be a suitable paper for a discussion club.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:52 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Sunday, January 22, 1956

Worked all day and late into the evening on the 3rd galley of the bibliography. Almost finished it.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:53 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Monday, January 23, 1956

At the office this morning.

Worked on the bibliography, finished it, and packed it for return to Berkeley.

Also finished the indexing of chapter 10.

Tuesday, January 24, 1956

At the office this morning.

Indexed chapter 11 today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:54 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, January 25, 1956

Went to Los Angeles this morning on the 9 AM train and returned at 6:05. Attended a Founders meeting, also looked up a few things in the library.

Today I received from the Press the first finished signature-pp133-164. It looks very satisfactory.

Also Jennings advised me that a correction sent in for p. 598 (vol. 1, chapter 9, grillidae should be gryllidae) was too late to be fixed. Well, there could be more glaring errors than this.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:23 PM
  • pamg 09/14/2012 11:57 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, January 26, 1956

At the office this morning.

Spent most of the afternoon preparing a financial report for the zoo, which I presented at much too great a length at the Zoo board meeting tonight.

Today I received from Mrs. Carroll the latest proof of the frontispiece of volume 2. Also from Jennings the folio's containing pp 1-32 and 101-132.

Friday, January 27, 1956

At the office this morning.

Today finished indexing chapter 12 except for copying a few slips.

Saturday, January 28, 1956

Worked all day on indexing Chapter 13 and made fair progress. It's a long chapter and difficult to index to avoid over-or under indexing.

Recd 3 more vol 1 signatures, 165-196, 197-228, 293-324.

Sunday, January 29, 1956

Keith Murray worked in the basement today on Hypsiglena.

Finished the indexing of chapter 13 and made a start on chapter 14

Went to a concert of the Boston Pops Orchestra tongihts.

Monday, January 30, 1956

At a library commission meeting all morning.

Finished making the index slips for chapters 14 and 15.

Received signature 261-292.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 12:06 AM

Tuesday, January 31, 1956

At the office this morning. Craig Reynolds called to discuss the Kiwanis meeting for next Friday.

Mrs. Hoover called this afternoon to talk over the Zoo's financial reports.

Worked on indexing of chapter 16. Made a complete list of references of Indian tribes, with page numbers. Quite a job. Took all afternoon and most of the evening.

Page Edit History:

Wednesday, February 1, 1956

At a Public Utilities Commission Meeting all day.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 12:10 AM

Thursday, February 2, 1956

Jennings called this morning, principally to discuss the progress with the index, and the effect it would have on the publication date. I told him I thought March 1st was the best that could be hoped for.

Received today a dummy of the copy of volume 1.

Spent all day at hearings of rate matters before the Public Utilities Commission.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:15 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Friday, February 3, 1956

At the office all morning.

Spoke to the Kiwanis Club at La Mesa at noon. Subject rattlesnakes.

Recd 3 more signature today.

Went to a meeting of the Zoo Research Committee tonight.

Nothing accomplished on the index today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:17 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Saturday, February 4, 1956

Worked all day and late into the evening indexing chapter 16. Made some progress.

Heard from the State Chamber that the meeting on Thursday next was called off so wrote Rita Carroll and Jennings that I wouldn't be up next week.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:18 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Sunday, February 5, 1956

Worked all day indexing chapter 16 and finished it. Developed some new techniques, better use of different weights of side heads. Should have done this sooner.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:20 PM

Monday, February 6, 1956

At the office all morning. Discussion of finances with Bert Lynch.

Company directors meeting this noon. Lasted until 2:30. Then a discussion of gas supply matters until 3:30.

Made a start today on indexing chapter 17.

Received three or four signatures from Berkeley.

Finished indexing chapter 17, and started on 18.

Also did accounts today.

Wednesday, February 8, 1956

Went to Los Angeles this morning on the 9 o'clock train. Meeting of the directors of Founder's Insurance Co.. Returned on the 5:30. Checked one or two items at the library.

Thursday, February 9, 1956

At the office this morning.

Finished the writing of slips for chapter 18.

Also made slips for all correspondents for both volumes, a formidable bunch. Worked until late at night on this.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:26 PM

Friday, February 10, 1956

At the office this morning.

Worked today on the index slips for correspondents, which was almost finished.

Charity Ball at Coronado tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:26 PM
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:27 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Saturday, February 11, 1956

Finished the correspondents index, ready to copy for Miss Molloy. Spent more than half a day running down possible errors in names and initials. This required looking up the old original letters. Found 7 errors in volume 2, not too late to change; and 13 errors in volume 1, too late to correct.

The first page proof of the Bibliography was sent down from Berkeley, arriving today. Looks pretty clean. It turns 141 printed pages; the original estimate was 130 pages. Not too bad a guess.

Made a start on the method of indexing the rattler subspecies.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:31 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Sunday, February 12, 1956

Worked all day on the page proofs of the Bibliography. Finished checking; got a few corrections that had been missed at Berkeley. However, it is a very clean and satisfactory proof.

In the evening drafted letters to Carroll and Jennings. The latter contained such corrections in Volume 2 that have been developed in checking Indian tribes, botanical names, and correspondents names and initials.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:33 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Monday, February 13, 1956

Mailed back the page proof of the Bibliography this morning.

At the office this morning.

Natural History Museum Board met this afternoon.

Went to a concert - Virtuoso de Roma - this evening.

Made a final decision today as to how to index the rattlers themselves. Will index under individual subspecies.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:35 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Tuesday, February 14, 1956

At the office this morning.

Made considerable progress with the index today.

Saw the article about me in the March issue of "Holiday" today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:36 PM

Wednesday, February 15, 1956

At the office this morning.

Today I finished making the index slips for the rattler subspecies.

Received from Berkeley the roman numbered pages for volume 2, the page proofs.

Thursday, February 16, 1956

At the office in the morning.

Worked on the index today cleaning up miscellaneous items.

Also corrected the roman numbered sheets of volume 2 and got them ready to return to Berkeley.

Page Edit History:

Friday, February 17, 1956

At the office this morning.

On television, channel 8, for a couple of minutes at 2:48 this afternoon. Staged by Art. Bell, it was little more than an ad for "holiday".

Received 10 tear sheets of the article in Holiday.

Sent back to Berkeley the roman numeral material from vol. 2.

Donald Darling called for about an hour this afternoon. He formerly worked for the San Antonio Zoo.

Despite these interruptions, I today finished the final survey of volume 1 for index citations.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:28 PM

Saturday, February 18, 1956

Worked all day in indexing. Finished the final run-over for certain miscellaneous items. So the slips are finally finished. Started the preparation of a bunch of boxes for alphabetical segregation.

Went to Scholia tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 01:57 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Sunday, February 19, 1956

Was on television today, channel 10 at 11:15 for a few minutes to advertise engineers week.

Worked the rest of the day and until midnight on the index. Segregated all the slips alphabetically. Also wrote up the A section as a sample for Jennings to comment on.

Tuesday, February 21, 1956

Solar board of directors meeting this morning; then a short time at the office.

At 4 went to a bond issue steering committee meeting in the mayor's office.

Baby sat this evening. Otherwise spent all available time on the index putting slips in alphabetical order.

Dentist appointment at 11:30 and at 12:30 talked to the Wednesday Club on Smog.

Monday, February 27, 1956

Today I received the final signatures for volume 1 except the preliminary or roman numeral pages. All looks good except some of the mitchelli pictures look light.

Also received the corrected sample index that had been sent to Berkeley. This changed quite a few things so that the sheets already done will require a good many modifications.

Spent morning at the office.

Continued indexing and finished down to and including G. This includes changes per letter from Berkeley on C to G.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:29 PM
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:12 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Tuesday, February 28, 1956

At the office in the morning.

Went to a bond-issue meeting at El Cortez from 2 to 3:30. Largely a waste of time.

Otherwise worked on the index. Finished H and started I.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:30 PM
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:13 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, February 29, 1956

At the office this morning. Worked on a speech on the use of atomic energy for power generation for the La Mesa Rotary Club. Delivered this at noon. It was a bust; it's too technical and dry to be of interest. Too dry and full of figures.

Worked on the index in the afternoon and evening and got partly through L and M.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:15 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, March 1, 1956

At the office this morning. Several conferences took considerable time.

Spent the rest of the day and evening on indexing. Finished L and almost finished M

Got C back from Miss Molloy today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:17 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Friday, March 2, 1956

Received today the first signature fo Vol. 2, (pp 721-752).

Spent the morning at the office. The rest of the day and evening on the index. Got as far as O; almost finished it.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:23 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Saturday, March 3, 1956

Today received 3 more signatures of volume 2 (pp. 753-848). Also a sample of the Index to show typographical form.

Started out this morning on a trip with Chickering at 8:45. Went out via 395 to San Luis Rey Valley, then up the Valley to Warners where we took cottages and had lunch. In the afternoon drove out to Borrego via the new Narrows road. Drove around the valley then home (Warners) via Banner, Julian, and Santa Ysabel. Arrived at 4:30. Rested the rest of the afternoon.

Many frogs and toads calling tonight. Saw one live lizard. No DOR snakes.

192 miles today.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:28 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Sunday, March 4, 1956

Started out with Chickering this morning at 9. Went up to Palomar. Went to the observatory, its museum and the public camp ground near Doane Valley. Came home via Rincon, Valley Center, and Escondido. Had lunch at Town and Country. Arrived at 1:30. 10.5 miles today. Nothing seen.

Spent the afternoon catching up.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/15/2012 02:35 PM

Monday, March 5, 1956

Meeting of the finance committee this mornign and directors at noon. Otherwise worked on index and partly finished P. Miss Molloy returned D-F today.

Had a telephone call from Bogert today.

At the office all morning.

Worked on indexing. Got as far as half way through the R's.

  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, March 7, 1956

At the office this morning. Took Amasa Bull of Chicago to lunch. Finally finished indexing the R's. Also wrote a long letter to Mrs. Ash of the Press.

Saturday, March 17, 1956

Spent a busy day on the index from 8:30 AM to 11:30 P.M.

Got a reply from Jennings concerning the deletions. He wants me to go to Berkeley, which I shall do next Thursday.

Miss Molloy finished copying the last slips today. As usual it is a relief to have two copies of original material like the index stored at two different points, so there is no chance for loss.

Received 3 signatures of volume 2 from Berkeley today.

Finished going over Jennings corrections and deletions in the A-F section and returned it to Berkeley with my reversals. Also sent him the G-Z section by air-mail special delivery.

Started cross-checking the cross-references, using the duplicate copy. Also putting in dual page numbers for the center heads.

Thursday, March 22, 1956

Arrived at the University Press at 9:15 and remained there until 4:30. Had a very busy and constructive day.

Most of the time was taken up in going over the Index with Jennings. Most of our differences were compromised. The results are quite satisfactory to me. We first went into generalities, then through the index from A to Z. I made many marginal notes and now face the difficult and time consuming task of incorporating all of our agreed changes into the manuscript. He wanted the ms by April 15, but I told him frankly that this was probably impossible as I was faced with other postponed matters. (income tax among others) that could no longer be postponed.

I was presented with the first bound copy--finished in every particular--of volume 1, which made this a red-letter day for it produced a feeling of actual accomplishment.

Had several brief conferences with Mrs. Carroll. My inquiry about the vignette for the bibliography came too.

Saturday, March 24, 1956

Spent the day on the Index. At Phil's for dinner.

Today I finished checking the direct cross-references. But I have learned since the index was finished how important it is to cross-check the same thought or subject entered under different key words. Often the pages cited may be quite different. So this is what I am working on now. It's a slow process and in any case can never be entirely complete.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/16/2012 12:42 PM

Sunday, March 25, 1956

Worked hard all day and late into the evening on the Index, picking up the differing page references on the same subject but under different key words. Often these don't agree. This is a very time consuming job, but is very necessary, as properly done, it adds greatly to the completeness of the Index. For the whole day I got only from M to Q. (I had begun at M, as the prior letters had been partly done.

Friday, March 30, 1956

At the office this morning. Several long discussions of company affairs.

In the afternoon and late into the night I worked on the ''rattle'' entry in the index. This has required a fantastic amount of time to complete. The improvement has been very great--probably at least 100% from the standpoint of the user, but if this were a fair sample and the same detailed methods were continued, the completion of the index would require a couple of months. I am much concerned with the situation.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

May 17th, continued

cited fields around Cantel until long after it was quite dark. Nothing was seen; the road was frequently wet from rain.

Finally went back to Saltdale, dropped off the manager, who has been with us, and started east via Garlock toward Randsburg.

1 long nose, clarus type, but plenty of red between the black bnds. 9:30, quite dark (PDST), 72 degrees F, 4 mi. west of Rand Siding, Kern County.

1 Scute, small DOR 4 mi. S. of Atolia. had eaten a mouse.
1 [Leopard lizard]] DOR 6 mi S. of Atolia.
1 Gopher L DOR 5 mi S. of Kramer Jnct.

Reached San Bernardino and put up at an auto court at 12:30.

Miles today 391.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/16/2012 02:32 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, May 17, 1956

At the office this morning. Jennings called and said he wanted to curtail down to a couple of sentences, the introduction to the index. I promised to consider the matters as soon as a letter he had written arrived.

At noon started out for Saltdale, Kern County, with Dave Miller and Larry. A clear warm day. Went via 395 to Johannesburg and then west to Saltdale. It was warm and overcast in San Diego.
1 Pyrrhus L squirming Moosa Canyon brush. It had eaten a mammal. It was in fine condition but I couldn't get it off the road quick enough to prevent its being ruined by a truck.
1 gopher L DOR 13 mi. D. of Kramer Jnct, light brush desert
1 gopher M DOR 7 mi S. of Atolia, light brush desert
Larry and I hunted lizards in rubbish at Saltdale and got 1 P. platyrhinos, 1 Uta s. stejnegeri and 1 X. vigilis. Several other Utas were seen. It was cool and overcast at Saltdale and there were occasional showers all evening, which ruined our collecting.

We started out on the evening drive about 7:00 and drove around amount culti-

(continued on May 16th)

Thursday, May 24, 1956

Checked my baggage at the East Bay terminal, then went to the Light and Power Council, my first meeting in a long time. Lunch at the Bohemian Club. Went over to Berkeley in a PGRE Cadillac. Conferred with Mrs. Carroll, Mrs. Bunting, John Goetz, Quail Hawkins. Settled many points. Goetz claims that all delays since the original Dec. date are due to the index, which is certainly stretching it. The index is now in the shop, including the introduction. Goetz promised more signatures from vol. 2.

Rode back to SF with Mrs. Carroll, then took a taxi to 55 Fifth Ave. A.J. and I had dinner at the Rancho. Also saw Dorrie's new house from the outside.

Saturday, June 2, 1956

Getting ready for a trip to Borrego in the morning.

In the afternoon at 2:10 started from the Pine Street house of the Millers with the whole tribe including the three kids for a trip to Borrego. Was quite warm in town. Went via 395 and the Poway turnoff.

1 Red diamond M DOR grass Poway
1 gopher L DOR Brush Poway
1 gopher L DOR grass Ramona
1 Patch nose M DOR Trees Banner
1 Leopard lizard DOR 2 mi. S. of Borrego miles to here 96

It was hot in Borrego. We had some trouble finding accomodations but finally put up at the Hacienda Motel.

Started on the evening drive at 7:15, Sundown. It seemed ideal; quite warm, no wind, no moon. But they weren't out. We went via the new south east road to the Co. line beyond Benson's dry Lake; then down the spur to the gypsum mine gate; back via the Narrows to Yaqui Well then over the Yaqui Pass to Borrego, then out to the end of the pavement on the Clark Lake Road and then home. Total miles in the evening drive 83; elapsed time 4-1/4 hrs. (Continued on June 3rd)

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 04:51 PM
  • pamg 09/16/2012 03:41 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Sunday, June 3, 1956

Started home from Borrego at 10 AM. It was quite warm. Went via Julian, Ramona, Poway and 395.

1 Red racer L DOR Top of Sentenac. Lt. brush
1 Red diamond M DOR Top of Sentenac. Lt brush
1 Long nose S DOR Poway brush
1 Gopher S DOR Poway brush

Reached home at 1 PM. Spent the afternoon resting and putting stuff away.
Miles today 92
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
June 2, Continued

Reached the Co. line beyond Benson at 7:55 and the Gypsum gate at 8:45. It was then quite dark.
1 Coleonyx lost 4 mi N of the gate
1 Leaf nose S COR 5 mi. S of Ocotillo 94 degrees 9:00 PM
1 Coleonyx COR 1 mi. W of Ocotillo 9:30
1 Coleonyx COR 9 mi. W of Ocotillo 10:00
1 Leaf nose S COR to Yaqui Pass 10:30
1 Leaf nose S DOR top Yaqui Pass

Home at 10:30. A very poor night with excellent condiitons. Maybe a little on the warm side.

Friday, July 6, 1956

At the office this morning.

Took lunch with Shaw and Dr. Kai Curry-Lindahl of Stockholm, Sweden. Then spent the afternoon reading a paper by him on the temperature tolerances of African Congo agamids and wrote out criticisms thereon. He thinks that the agamids can stand higher temperatures than our desert reptiles, but as he took no anal readings, I think he failed to prove his thesis.

Dinner at home tonight to Robt. Shaw the chorus conductor and others.

Thursday, August 30; 1956

Arrived at Oakland one hour late. Taxied to Berkeley SP Station, parked luggage, then to U.C. Press.

Mrs. Carroll was not in so talked first to Callenbach of the promotion department, then with Mrs. Bunting and Boris Sheiman, salesman for the California-Arizona area. A number of publicity proposals were discussed in detail. Various new items, including foreign distribution via the State Dept. or some other govt agency or the UN were mentioned. Discussed review copies and the newspapers and magazines that had already expressed an interest. The outlook is good.

Jennings was in Los Angeles for good; Goetz on his vacation.

Went to lunch with Mrs. Carroll and talked over the jacket. While in Miss Carroll's office, the second page proof of the index that I had mailed on Aug. 2nd was delivered to her. It has been clearly marked "Returned proof with letter enclosed" but never-the less had mixed with books being returned to the Press and there had

Friday, September 28, 1956

At the office this morning.

Got some separates catalogued.

Also started to arrange the Sharp and Dohme collection of articles on snake bite. This collection arrived Aug. 10, 1954. I have always regretted that I did not receive this material prior to beginning work on Chapters 11-13 (snake bite0 for they would have been improved thereby, and certainly the bibliography would have been expanded to a beneficial degree. As it was the material arrived when the snake-bite chapters were receiving their final over hauling. There was great pressure to sent this material to Berkeley and only the most important of the newly available references could be included, even by reference.

Saturday, October 6, 1956

--------------------------------------------------------
Oct. 9, continued

Called Chickering but he had already left for lunch so I lunched alone at the Cleft.

Then went to a meeting of the Calif. Development Committee of the State Chamber. Only Russell (S.P) and Sullivan (PT&T) were there. The meeting lasted only from 2 to 2:30. I made a few suggestions as to lines of research. Went out to the Civic Auditorium where the American College of Surgeons were holding a convention. Said to be 12, 000 of them. Went to the booth of the American Association of University Presses. Found Miss Quail Hawkins of the U.C. Press in charge. They had a copy of the book (2 vols). Discussed sales and promotion with her. She is very optimistic.

Went down to the Sheraton-Palace and called Mrs. Carroll.

(continued on Oct. 7)

Oct 9th - continued from Oct. 6

Then got in touch with Dr. R. I. Harris of Toronto who had written me and had several rattler questions to ask. We talked abut a fatal massasauga case in Ontario and other rattler matters from 4:45 to 5:30. Then he began to get a little nervous and I left. He was working on a paper on flat feet to be delivered next day at the convention.

Left SF at 9 P.M.

Monday, October 8, 1956

Went to the office in the morning; then home to meet Bryant Evans, Science Editor of the S.D. Union. He came at 10:30. We watched the finish of the wonderful "perfecto" game pitched by Don Larsen. Then he interviewed me until 1 PM, partly on the rattler book, partly on my personal experiences in Herpetology. He was particularly interested in yarns and incidents. He made a lot of notes. I hope it comes out all right. I loaned him by unbound copy of vol. II.

Left for San Francisco on the 3:30 train. Called Ed in LA.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/21/2012 10:28 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Tuesday, October 9, 1956

Arrived in San Francisco at 8:30. Called Dorie from the East Bay Terminal. Went over to Berkeley arriving at the U.C. Press at 9:45. Saw Goetz, Callenbach, and Mrs. Bunting and went over many problems concerning publicity and promotion. Saw the first finished copy of vol II, another land-mark. Also saw proofs of the jackets for the first time. The jackets have not been run yet as the green back grounds are not satisfactory to Mr. Carroll. She wants the green lighter and brighter. Volume II looks OK. The colophon had been forgotten and had to be tipped in. I arranged for various things to be sent me at S.D., including a copy of vol. II. Finished at the Press at about 11:15. Did not succeed in talking to the man who will have charge of shipping the free copies to SD. Left word that I thought the shipment should be made by truck.

Called Tova Heyneman but she had an engagement so I didn't see her. Went back to San Francisco, arriving at noon.

(Continued on Oct. 6)

Saturday, October 20, 1956

In Los Angeles.

Worked on the alphabetizing of the index cards of the separates I had lately catalogued.

In the evening went to a performance of Simon Boccnegra, the first time I had ever heard this opera. The usual fantastic Verdi plot very difficult to follow even with an adequate story outline. The music is very beautiful; it deserves to be heard more often. With Leonard Warren, Renate Tobaldi, Boris Christoff, Roberto Turrini, et al, including our local Christine Krooskos in a minute part.

Sunday, October 21, 1956

This morning we visited Donnie and Mickie in their new house in the Brentwood district.

Then attended a matinee performance of LaBoheme. Enjoyed the old times, although Licia Albanese was not what she once ws. Others included Jan Peerce, Quilico, Blankenburg, Italo Tajo, Mary Gray, etc.

Had loaded the car in the morning and got started southbound a few minutes after 6. Arrived a little before 9. The traffic although dense wasn't too difficult, except in the stretch between El Toro and Serra. We were unfortunate enough to get caught in a procession behind a slow car, with no chance to pass in the entire two-lane distance.

Page Edit History:

Tuesday, October 23, 1956

At the office for a short time this morning; also went to the library to check progress with the book exhibit with Miss Head. Started for Los Angeles about 11. Put up at the Aster Motel as usual.

In the evening went to a performance of Falstaff: Leonard Warren, Elizabeth Schwarzkopf, Guarrera, Schuh, Campora, Roggero, Dominguez, Assandri, de Pavlis, Moscona et al. Despite the superiority claimed by professional musicians and critics for Verdi's third period, this is certainly far less enjoyable by the plain opera goers than his middle period operas. The ensemble numbers are wonderful but still it is an opera one would not choose to see twice if others were available. The plot is against it, not because it's light but because it's silly.

Alas, Schwartzkopf, although still beautiful has put on weight.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/22/2012 12:55 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, October 24, 1956

In Los Angeles. Hung around the motel all day.

In the evening went to a performance of Tosca. With Tebaldi, RIchard Martell, Colzani Cehanovsky, Palangi, de Pavlis et al. Tebaldi had a better voice than Dorothy Kirsten, but is not so good or plausible an actress. Martell was good, but the others hardly up to past performances. Despite the melodrama, Tosca has a plot that hangs together. One can easily see why these Puccini operas retain their popularity.

For some unknown reason a group in the audience booed the conductor Curiel on two occasions.

Heard today that the lack of books in San Diego, after last Sunday's publicity, led book dealers to substitute other books on inquiry from purchasers, a very objectionable procedure.

  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Monday, October 29, 1956

At the office this morning.

There still seems to be a shortage of books at the book dealers; none have exhibits.

Dr. Askew called with regard to postponing the next meeting.

Quail Hawkins called; has arrived to run the U.C.Press exhibit at the California Library Assn. Convention. This will be at the Grant Hotel.

Margaret Bancroft came around to have her copy autographed.

Ruth Clarke called and said Vrooman still didn't have the books she ordered for her self and Carghill. I told her I would autograph them whenever the books became available.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/22/2012 01:18 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Tuesday, October 30, 1956

Went to the office this morning then to the Public Library to check the book exhibit, now finished.

A crate containing 50 copies of the book arrived by truck this morning. They were well packed. Started for Los Angeles with GG at 11:45 and arrived at 2:15. Hung around the Aster Motel for the rest of the afternoon.

In the evening went to a performance of Boris Godounoff. It was a good but not outstanding presentation. The symbolic scenery was not appropriate to an opera so dependent on pagentry. Boris Christoff, the lead, was not up to advance publicity. Others in the case were Rosalind Nadell (Feodor), Jeannine Crader (Xenia), June Wilkins (Nurse), Cruzi (Schouisky), Cehanovsky, Moscona, Leurs, Oralia Dominguez (Marion), Hana Hotter (Rangoni), Alvary, Lachona, Katherine Hilgenberg (Innkeeper) etc.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/22/2012 01:31 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Wednesday, October 31, 1956

Spent the morning in the motel. Called on Ed in the afternoon. Sat in the lobby of the Townhouse. Gave him a copy of the book.

In the evening heard a presentation of Francesca da Remini. Never had seen it before. Beautiful orchestration (mostly too loud) but on the whole an unsatisfactory opera, to be seen only once. Leyla Gencer (Turkish Soprano), Martell, Colzani, Curzi, and others.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/22/2012 01:37 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Thursday, November 1, 1956

Drove down from Los Angeles starting at 9 and arriving a little before noon. Went to the office in the afternoon and to the library to check the exhibits.

Saw a copy of Time with a review of the book in the "Science" section. On the whole a very satisfactory write-up, well suited to the clientele of the magazine.

In the evening went to Madame Butterfly at the Fox. On the whole a very satisfactory presentation. With Dorothy Kirsten, Guiseppe Campora, Margaret Roggero, Louis Quilico, Assandri, Ligeti, Cehanovsky, et al. Dorothy was in good voice. The tenor Campora had a cold but still did very well. Quilico was one of the best Sharplesses I have heard.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/22/2012 01:45 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Friday, November 2, 1956

At the office this morning. Discussed gas supply and other matters with Dillin.

Gave copies of the book to Miss Schneberger and Les Kobler. Mailed copied to Charles M. Bogent and Karl P. Schmidt.

Presided at a meeting of the Trustees's section, California Library Association at noon at the Grant Motel.

Went up to the Zoo in the afternoon and discussed the free copies with Schroeder and Chuck Shaw; also accounting methods.

In the evening attended a dinner of the Trustees's section, California Library Association.

Talked over two television shows for next Sunday.

Saturday, November 3, 1956

Spent most of the day on letters and similar chores.

The Zoo brought around 69 sets of the books of which 5 were autographed and sent back, leaving 64.

Dr. Charles S. Marsden, who had given the first order in San Francisco at the Surgeon's Convention, brought around his set to be autographed for his son.

Sunday, November A, 1956

Spent the morning packing books for shipment: Hubbs, Stebbins, Grant, Slevin. Cowles, Can Rysel, Oliver, Bilderback, Brattstrom, Chickering. These are the most essential early ones.

Took part in 2 television programs; Zoorama which took from 2 to 4:15; actually on the air from 3:30 to 4; and Harold Keene's news broadcast; on the air from 5:50 to 6:00 but took from 5 to 6:15.

Thursday, November 29, 1956

Meeting of the California State Chamber of Commerce in San Francisco. I presided at a meeting of the Natural Resources Committee from 10 until noon. Then attended a luncheon addressed by Admiral Ben Moreel.

Visited Stacey's bookstore on Market Street, a specialist on scientific books. No rattler books. Went to the San Francisco Public Library and worked there from 3 to 5. Picked up three items. Rattler book not in their catalogue yet.

Rested in the evening.
-------------------------------------------------
(Nov. 30, continued)

Talked over the Popular Science Monthly request.

Went back to SF and attended a lunch and board of directors meeting of the Cal. State C of C.

No rattler books at Paul Elders or New begins.

Saw the Moore Paterson fight in SP restuarant at 3rd & Townsend under difficulties. My filet of sole outlasted Moore.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/22/2012 02:49 PM
  • pamg 09/22/2012 02:49 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:59 PM

Friday, November 30, 1956

Went over to Berkeley this morning and arrived at the Press at 9:40. Stayed until 11. Saw Mrs. Bunting, Callenbach, Mrs. Carroll, Goetz, and Lillienthal. Talked publicity and promotion with Mrs. Bunting. Also reviews. The New York Times appears hopeful as they requested a second copy by phone to be mailed. Mrs. Bunting told me that 480 (plus or minus) sets had been sold up to Nov. 14. She seemed pleased with the sales. She showed me several clips and short reviews including the San Antonio Express and News of Oct. 28, 1956. Said to be sure to let them know next time I came up as 2 or 3 people wanted to interview me. Told them about Stacy.

Had quite a chat with Lillienthal about the book. Told him I was pleased with all my relations with the Press. Told him I thought U.C. should have its own Style Book. He wanted to know particularly how I happened to choose the U.C. Press

(continued on opposite page)
